ate": 1768506606, "magika": "PEBIN", "crowdsourced_ai_results": [{"category": "code_insight", "verdict": "malicious", "analysis": "The analyzed binary is a highly sophisticated ransomware sample, specifically identifying as the Hermes ransomware family. It exhibits classic destructive behaviors designed to maximize impact and prevent recovery. Key malicious activities include: 1) Backup destruction: It executes commands via vssadmin to delete Volume Shadow Copies and resize shadow storage limits to 401MB (a technique to ensure shadow copies are purged and cannot be recreated easily). It also recursively deletes files with extensions related to backups and virtual disks (.VHD, .bac, .bak, .wbcat, .bkf, .set, .win, .dsk). 2) Persistence: It modifies the Windows Registry (HKCU\\...\\Run) to ensure it executes on startup, using the deceptive name 'svchos' (masquerading as svchost). 3) Ransomware functionality: It creates a ransom note named 'DECRYPT_INFORMATION.txt' on the Desktop, uses the 'Microsoft Enhanced RSA and AES Cryptographic Provider' for file encryption, and marks encrypted files with the 'HERMES' string. 4) Evasion and Cleanup: It employs dynamic API resolution to hide its imports and utilizes a self-deleting batch script (TIMEOUT/del %0) to remove its original loader after deployment. Relevant IOCs include the registry key 'svchos', the ransom note 'DECRYPT_INFORMATION.txt', and the unique identifier 'UNIQUE_ID_DO_NOT_REMOVE'.", "source": "palm", "id": "e08fc761cc22953de7fcc1684b7424755fa52f361dd5c6605b1469a80cb858bb-file-palm"}]}}}